<COREF ID="21" TYPE="IDENT">The argument</COREF> turns on the discovery in 1909 of <COREF ID="0" TYPE="IDENT">an amazing fossil quarry high in the Canadian Rockies called the Burgess Shale</COREF> .
<COREF ID="0" TYPE="IDENT">Here</COREF> , in an area smaller than a city block , lay buried <COREF ID="4" TYPE="IDENT">traces of countless weird creatures that had frolicked more than 500 million years ago -- creatures whose anatomical variety far exceeded what can be found in all <COREF ID="2" TYPE="IDENT">the world 's</COREF> oceans today</COREF> .
<COREF ID="4" TYPE="IDENT">Such an embarrassment of riches</COREF> was inconceivable to the man who discovered <COREF ID="0" TYPE="IDENT">the Burgess Shale</COREF> , one Charles Doolittle Walcott .
The received Darwinian wisdom of the day said that animals living so long ago must be simple in design , limited in scope and ancestral to contemporary species .
Accordingly , the hidebound traditionalist reconstructed <COREF ID="18" TYPE="IDENT">hypothetical organisms</COREF> from the <COREF ID="0" TYPE="IDENT">Burgess</COREF> fossils in such a way that <COREF ID="18" TYPE="IDENT">they</COREF> could be shoehorned into familiar categories .
